x;">Members of the Democratic National Committee gathered in Washington ove=
r the weekend to
elect a new chairman, <strong>Ken Martin</strong>, the little-known, 51-yea=
r-old leader of Minnesota=E2=80=99s Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party, a white =
guy with a nice haircut and an accent straight out of the latest season of =
<em>Fargo</em>. The chairman=E2=80=99s race was mostly a behind-the-scenes =
affair obsessed over by party activists and journalists, but ignored by the=
 general public and the vast majority of exhausted Democratic voters. The e=
lection jockeying was peak inside-baseball, with each candidate
rolling out endorsements from this D.N.C. member or that. Martin, a known c=
ommodity inside the D.N.C., won a dominant majority of the party=E2=80=99s =
nearly 450 members, easily dispatching his next-strongest opponent, Wiscons=
in Democratic Party chairman <strong>Ben Wikler</strong>.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">As a prize, the D.N.C. gig has lost luster over the years. In the era be=
fore social media, a party chair could model oneself a
national leader by going on cable news or the Sunday shows and jousting wit=
h his or her Republican counterpart. With their party out of the White Hous=
e, former chairs <strong>Terry McAuliffe</strong> and <strong>Howard Dean</=
strong> routinely made news by going on <em>Hardball</em> and punching at <=
strong>George W. Bush</strong>. But as entertaining as they were back in th=
e day, the reality <em>today</em> is that being a party chair=E2=80=94D.N.C=
=2E or R.N.C.=E2=80=94isn=E2=80=99t about driving a message or being the
party=E2=80=99s puppet master. It=E2=80=99s about fundraising, building sta=
te party organizations, managing the logistics of a presidential primary, e=
nduring tedious phone calls with donors, and mollifying needy activists and=
 coalition groups. Martin, to his credit, says he=E2=80=99s planning to be =
an inside player, not an attention fiend or a message maven. =E2=80=9CI=E2=
=80=99m not here to win the argument, I=E2=80=99m here to win elections,=E2=
=80=9D he told MSNBC. Like <strong>Tom Perez</strong>, the D.N.C. chairman =
in <strong>Donald
Trump</strong>=E2=80=99s first term, Martin will not become a household nam=
e, which seems just fine with him=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">What struck me about the D.N.C. e=
lection was that the committee members totally brushed off a slew of nation=
al Democratic politicians=E2=80=94<strong>Nancy Pelosi</strong>, <strong>Ha=
keem Jeffries</strong>, <strong>Chuck Schumer</strong>, <strong>Gretchen Wh=
itmer</strong>, <strong>Andy Beshear</strong>=E2=80=94who endorsed Wikler, =
a
guy who=E2=80=99d gained a national profile by winning tight elections in b=
attleground Wisconsin. D.N.C. members didn=E2=80=99t care. The D.N.C. is a =
clubby and insular outfit, sure, with lifer activists who run the show inst=
ead of the politicians we see on the news. But the rejection of Wikler and =
his big-name allies suggested that members weren=E2=80=99t interested in he=
avy-handed advice from the party brahmins who got absolutely smoked by the =
G.O.P. last year. Even crusty D.N.C. members were saying no thanks to the
